'''Ryan Christie''' (born 22 February 1995) is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] or [[winger (association football)|winger]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Ryan Christie Positions|url=https://www.footballcritic.com/ryan-christie/profile/34073|access-date=10 November 2023}}</ref> for [[Premier League]] club [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].

Christie began his career with [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Inverness Caledonian Thistle]] before joining Celtic in 2015, and had two spells on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] at [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]. He has also represented the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21]] and full national teams.

==Club career==
===Inverness Caledonian Thistle===
Christie was born in [[Inverness]] in 1995; he is the son of footballer [[Charlie Christie]], who was playing for [[Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C.|Caledonian Thistle]] at the time and who had previously been a reserve player with [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].

Christie joined the Inverness Caledonian Thistle youth system aged 10,<ref>{{cite news|title=Club statement: Ryan Christie|url=http://ictfc.com/news/team-news/1606-ryan-christie|publisher=Inverness|date=27 September 2015|access-date=10 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171110172116/http://ictfc.com/news/team-news/1606-ryan-christie|archive-date=10 November 2017}}</ref> before eventually signing his first professional contract in 2011.<ref name="Ryan Christie sign his first professional contract">{{cite news|title=Christie's son among new youth signings|url=http://www.inverness-courier.co.uk/Sport/Football/Christies-son-among-new-youth-signings-13052011.htm|publisher=Inverness Courier|date=15 May 2011|access-date=18 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001233/http://www.inverness-courier.co.uk/Sport/Football/Christies-son-among-new-youth-signings-13052011.htm|archive-date=31 December 2013}}</ref> He signed a new deal with the club under [[Terry Butcher]], and was among several youngsters to be promoted to the club's first team.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kidderminster midfielder linked to move north|url=http://www.inverness-courier.co.uk/Sport/Football/Kidderminster-midfielder-linked-to-move-north-23052013.htm|publisher=Inverness Courier|date=24 May 2013|access-date=18 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518224548/http://www.inverness-courier.co.uk/Sport/Football/Kidderminster-midfielder-linked-to-move-north-23052013.htm|archive-date=18 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Butcher backing young players to shine in SPL next season|url=http://www.inverness-courier.co.uk/Sport/Football/Butcher-backing-young-players-to-shine-in-SPL-next-season-27062013.htm|publisher=Inverness Courier|date=27 June 2013|access-date=18 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140518224924/http://www.inverness-courier.co.uk/Sport/Football/Butcher-backing-young-players-to-shine-in-SPL-next-season-27062013.htm|archive-date=18 May 2014}}</ref>

Christie made his debut in the [[Scottish Premiership]] against Celtic on 29 December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Inverness CT 0–1 Celtic|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/25482616|publisher=BBC Sport|date=29 December 2013|access-date=23 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=45774|title=Ryan Christie – Football Stats – Celtic – Age 21 – Soccer Base}}</ref> He came on as a substitute in the 100th minute in the [[2014 Scottish League Cup Final|Scottish League Cup Final]] against [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]], a game that Inverness lost on penalties.<ref name=lc14>{{cite news|title=Aberdeen 0&nbsp;– 0 Inverness CT (AET, 4–2 on pen)|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26502621|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 March 2014|access-date=18 May 2014}}</ref> Despite this, Christie helped the club finish in the top-six of the [[Scottish Premiership]]. His first goal for Inverness came in a 2–1 loss against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] on 1 April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Inverness Caledonian Thistle 1&nbsp;– 2 Motherwell|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26727004|publisher=BBC Sport|date=1 April 2014|access-date=18 May 2014}}</ref> Christie added two more goals later in the season against [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]] and [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Inverness CT 1–1 Dundee United|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27168358|publisher=BBC Sport|date=3 May 2014|access-date=18 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Caley Thistle finish season on a high|url=http://www.inverness-courier.co.uk/Sport/Football/Caley-Thistle-finish-season-on-a-high-11052014.htm|publisher=Inverness Courier|date=11 May 2014|access-date=18 May 2014|archive-date=9 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009140901/http://www.inverness-courier.co.uk/Sport/Football/Caley-Thistle-finish-season-on-a-high-11052014.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref> After impressive displays for Inverness, Christie signed a new contract with the club at the end of the 2013–14 season.<ref>{{cite news|title=Inverness CT: Ryan Christie wins new two-year contract|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/27447162|publisher=BBC Sport|date=16 May 2014|access-date=16 May 2014}}</ref>

Christie scored his first goal of the 2014–15 season in a 2–0 win over [[Hamilton Academical F.C.|Hamilton Academical]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hamilton Academical 0–2 Inverness Caledonian Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28647037|publisher=BBC Sport|date=9 August 2014|access-date=23 June 2015}}</ref> Christie's performances against [[Dundee F.C.|Dundee]], Motherwell, Celtic, Kilmarnock and [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]] saw him win the [[List of Scottish Professional Football League monthly award winners|SPFL Young Player of the Month]] for August.<ref name="Christie award">{{cite news |title=Inverness CT win trio of SPFL monthly awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29164340 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 September 2014|access-date=12 September 2014}}</ref> During a match against [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]] in October 2014, he was sent-off for the first time in his career&nbsp;– being dismissed by referee [[Willie Collum]] for two-bookable offences.<ref>{{cite news|title=St Mirren 0–1 Inverness|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/29580111|publisher=BBC Sport|access-date=20 October 2014}}</ref> Christie added to his earlier success by winning the SPFL Young Player of the Month award for February 2015,<ref name="Christie again">{{cite news |title=Ross County's McIntyre and ICT's Christie win February awards|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/31896979 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 March 2015|access-date=16 March 2015}}</ref> and his eye-catching form over the whole season subsequently saw him shortlisted for the [[PFA Scotland Young Player of the Year|Young Player of the Year]] award.<ref name="Christie nominated">{{cite news |title=Celtic's Van Dijk & Johansen join Rooney & Stewart in award mix|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/32435212 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 April 2015|access-date=27 April 2015}}</ref> Although he didn't win that accolade, he was later honoured with the [[SFWA Young Player of the Year]] award.<ref name="SFWA"/> Christie started the [[2015 Scottish Cup Final]] and was later substituted for [[James Vincent (footballer)|James Vincent]], who scored the winning goal in a 2–1 victory over [[Falkirk F.C.|Falkirk]].<ref name="cup final"/> After the match, Christie described winning the Scottish Cup as ''"unbelievable, hard to put into words"''.

===Celtic===
====2015–16====
On 1 September 2015, Christie joined Celtic on a four-year deal. After signing for the Scottish champions, Christie was immediately sent back to Inverness on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ryan Christie: Celtic agree four-year deal for Inverness player|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/34106143|publisher=BBC Sport |date=1 September 2015|access-date=1 September 2015}}</ref> He sustained a knee injury against [[Motherwell F.C.|Motherwell]] in November, and was recalled by Celtic so he could work with their medical staff at their Lennoxtown training complex.<ref>{{cite news|last=Third|first=Paul|title=Celtic recall Ryan Christie early following injury|url=https://www.pressandjournal.co.uk/fp/sport/football/inverness-caledonian-thistle/750724/undefined-headline-1421/|access-date=18 January 2016|work=The Press and Journal|date=13 November 2015}}</ref> In December 2015, Celtic announced they would be recalling Christie from his loan spell at Inverness.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bean|first=Graham|title=Celtic recall Ryan Christie from Inverness loan|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/teams/celtic/celtic-recall-ryan-christie-from-inverness-loan-1-3983368|access-date=18 January 2016|work=The Scotsman|date=23 December 2015}}</ref>

Christie made his debut for Celtic on 23 January 2016 in their 3–1 win over [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]], coming on as an 88th-minute substitute for [[Stuart Armstrong]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Richard|title=Celtic 3 – 1 St Johnstone|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/35330974|access-date=24 January 2016|publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref>

====Aberdeen loans====
On 24 January 2017, Christie joined [[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]] on loan until the end of the 2016–17 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-transfer-news/celtic-starlet-ryan-christie-joins-9685094|title=Celtic starlet Ryan Christie joins Aberdeen on loan until end of the season|last=Jackson|first=Keith|date=24 January 2017|work=[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]|publisher=[[Trinity Mirror]]|access-date=24 January 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for Aberdeen on 4 February 2017, in a 2–0 win against [[Partick Thistle F.C.|Partick Thistle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Aberdeen 2–0 Partick Thistle|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38779181|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Davie|first=Scott|date=4 February 2017|access-date=4 February 2017}}</ref> He helped Aberdeen finish second in the [[2016–17 Scottish Premiership]] and progress to the [[2017 Scottish Cup Final]], but was unable to take part in the cup final because it was against his parent club Celtic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40001211 |first=Alasdair |last=Lamont |publisher=BBC Sport |title=Ryan Christie: Ineligible midfielder will not be in stands for Aberdeen v Celtic cup final |date=23 May 2017 |access-date=23 May 2017}}</ref>

Christie returned to Aberdeen on loan for most of the 2017–18 season, moving in June 2017 as part of a deal for [[Jonny Hayes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jonny Hayes: Celtic sign winger as Ryan Christie returns to Aberdeen on loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40292266|publisher=BBC Sport|date=17 June 2017|access-date=17 June 2017}}</ref>

====2018–19====
Christie returned to Celtic for the [[2018–19 in Scottish football|2018–19 season]]. [[Neil Lennon]], who returned to Celtic as manager later in the season, said in July 2019 that he had wanted to sign Christie for [[Hibernian F.C.|Hibernian]] during the summer of 2018 as part of a proposed deal for [[John McGinn]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/hibernian/hibs-missed-out-on-the-signing-of-ryan-christie-from-celtic-reveals-neil-lennon-1-4972696 |title=Hibs missed out on the signing of Ryan Christie from Celtic reveals Neil Lennon |first=Joel |last=Sked |work=The Scotsman |date=29 July 2019 |access-date=4 August 2019}}</ref> In the 2018–19 League Cup semi-final against [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] at [[Murrayfield Stadium|Murrayfield]], Christie won a penalty, caused a goalkeeping error and hit a "wonderful left-foot shot" leading to each goal in the eventual 3–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/46011352|title=Hearts 0–3 Celtic: 'Sensational' Ryan Christie seizes his opportunity |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 October 2018|access-date=28 October 2018}}</ref> Christie signed a new contract with Celtic in November 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46184135 |title=Celtic: Ryan Christie signs new three-year contract that 'tops off an amazing period' |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 November 2018 |access-date=23 November 2018}}</ref> On 2 December, he scored the only goal of the [[2018 Scottish League Cup Final]] at Hampden against former club Aberdeen.<ref name=lcf18/> His season ended abruptly on 14 April 2019 in the [[2018–19 Scottish Cup#Semi-finals|Scottish Cup semi-final]], again at Hampden against Aberdeen, when he suffered facial fractures in an aerial collision with opponent [[Dominic Ball]], who was sent off for the reckless nature of the challenge.<ref>[https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/celtic-star-ryan-christie-shares-14337444 Celtic star Ryan Christie shares gruesome photo showing damage from Dom Ball collision], Daily Record, 15 April 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/celtic/in-full/ryan-christie-to-undergo-facial-surgery-after-incident-in-celtic-aberdeen-scottish-cup-semi-final-1-4908540 Ryan Christie to undergo facial surgery after incident in Celtic-Aberdeen Scottish Cup semi-final], The Scotsman, 16 April 2019</ref>

====2019–20====
[[File:Rangers v Celtic 2982021 - 51411759880.jpg|thumb|right|Christie playing for [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] in 2021]]
Christie scored a hat-trick in a 7–0 win against [[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]] in the first game of the [[2019–20 Scottish Premiership]] season.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/aug/03/celtic-st-johnstone-scottish-premiership-match-report |title=Ryan Christie's hat-trick inspires Celtic to demolition of Saints |work=The Observer |date=3 August 2019 |access-date=4 August 2019}}</ref> In October 2020, he scored the opening goal of the [[2019–20 Scottish Cup]] semi-final against Aberdeen (delayed from its usual April scheduling due the [[COVID-19 pandemic in Scotland]], which also led to Celtic being awarded the Premiership title after the season was curtailed) with a curling left-footed shot from outside the penalty area – Celtic won 2–0.<ref>[https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/celtic/ryan-christie-looking-end-long-wait-scottish-cup-final-celtic-after-stunning-strike-semi-final-3021765 Ryan Christie looking to end long wait for Scottish Cup final with Celtic after stunning strike in semi-final], Andrew Smith, The Scotsman, 1 November 2020</ref> In [[2020 Scottish Cup Final|the final]] against Hearts he scored a very similar goal,<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fyt8dEhe1Ys Ryan Christie Goals v Aberdeen and Hearts], [[Scottish Cup]] official [[YouTube]] channel, 21 December 2020; retrieved 29 March 2021</ref> again the first of the match and with almost the same amount of time elapsed, but then missed his penalty in the subsequent shootout following a 3–3 draw after extra time; he was the only Celtic player to fail with his attempt as they won the trophy.<ref name=cup20>[https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/dec/20/celtic-hearts-scottish-cup-final-match-report Celtic win fourth straight Scottish Cup as Hazard's shootout saves break Hearts], Ewan Murray, The Guardian, 20 December 2020</ref>

=== Bournemouth ===
On 31 August 2021, Christie moved to England, joining [[EFL Championship]] club [[AFC Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] on a three-year contract, for a reported transfer fee of around £1.5 million.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Christie completes Cherries transfer|url=https://www.afcb.co.uk/news/first-team/christie-completes-cherries-transfer/?dm_i=47ot,1532o,gh7h0,57yy1,1|access-date=2021-08-31|website=AFCB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Transfer news: Celtic's Ryan Christie joins Bournemouth|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11743/12395778/transfer-news-celtics-ryan-christie-joins-bournemouth|access-date=2021-08-31|website=Sky Sports|language=en}}</ref> On 11 September 2021, Christie came off the bench to make his Bournemouth debut in the side's 3–0 win over [[Barnsley F.C.|Barnsley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/58444601|title=Bournemouth 3–0 Barnsley|website=bbc.co.uk|date=11 September 2021|access-date=12 September 2021}}</ref> On 8 October 2022, he scored his first [[Premier League]] goal in a 2–1 victory over [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Grounds |first=Ben |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12713595/bournemouth-2-1-leicester-ryan-christie-completes-second-half-turnaround-to-stun-foxes |title=Bournemouth 2–1 Leicester: Ryan Christie completes second-half turnaround to stun Foxes |publisher=Sky Sports |date=8 October 2022 }}</ref>

In April 2025, he sustained a groin injury which would sideline him for the remainder of the 2024–25 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/bournemouths-christie-out-season-after-undergoing-surgery-2025-04-11/ |title=Bournemouth's Christie out for the season after undergoing surgery |publisher=Reuters |date=11 April 2025 }}</ref>

==International career==
On 25 August 2014, Christie was called up by [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland U21]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Christie scores call-up to Scotland under-21s|url=http://www.highland-news.co.uk/Sport/Football/Inverness-Caley-Thistle/Christie-scores-call-up-to-Scotland-under-21s-25082014.htm|publisher=Highland News|date=25 August 2014|access-date=23 June 2015|archive-date=4 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304111338/http://www.highland-news.co.uk/Sport/Football/Inverness-Caley-Thistle/Christie-scores-call-up-to-Scotland-under-21s-25082014.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref> After being left on the bench against [[Slovakia national under-21 football team|Slovakia U21]], Christie finally made his Scotland U21 debut against [[Luxembourg national under-21 football team|Luxembourg U21]] on 9 September 2014, coming on as a substitute for [[Lewis Macleod (footballer)|Lewis Macleod]] in the second half, which Scotland U21 won 3–0.<ref>{{cite news|title=Luxembourg U21s 0 Scotland U21s 3: Boss Billy Stark sees hope for the future as Sporting Lisbon star Ryan Gauld gets off the mark|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/sport/football/football-match-reports/luxembourg-u21s-0-scotland-u21s-4187082|publisher=Daily Record|date=9 September 2014|access-date=23 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitbastats.com/scotlandu21/player.php?playerid=579 |title=Scotland U21 profile |publisher=Fitbastats.com|access-date=20 June 2017}}</ref>

Christie received his first call-up to the senior [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad for a friendly against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in November 2017,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41796933 |title=Scotland: Interim manager Malky Mackay calls up three new faces for friendly |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 October 2017 |access-date=31 October 2017}}</ref> and played the full 90 minutes of the 1–0 defeat.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41840573 |title=Scotland 0—1 Netherlands |work=BBC Sport |date=9 November 2017 |access-date=10 November 2017 }}</ref> He scored his first international goal on 16 November 2019, opening the scoring with a curling shot from outside the penalty area in a 2–1 away win over [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] in [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualification]].<ref>[https://www.glasgowtimes.co.uk/sport/18041459.amp/ Cyprus 1 Scotland 2: Steve Clarke's side benefit from early lucky break to move into third place in Group I], Glasgow Times, 16 November 2019</ref> In September 2020, he scored penalties in successive matches as Scotland drew with [[Israel national football team|Israel]]<ref>[https://prod.news.stv.tv/sport/scotland-1-1-israel-nations-league-campaign-begins-with-draw?top Scotland 1–1 Israel: Nations League campaign begins with draw], STV News, 4 September 2020</ref> and defeated the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] in the [[2020–21 UEFA Nations League]].<ref>[https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/international/czech-republic-1-scotland-2-david-marshall-heroics-and-woodwork-rescue-nations-league-victory-2964109 Czech Republic 1 Scotland 2: David Marshall heroics and woodwork to rescue in Nations League victory], The Scotsman, 7 September 2020</ref>

In October 2020, Christie was required to pull out of the Scotland squad for a [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying play-offs|Euro 2020 play-off]] semi-final against Israel after being in close contact with [[Stuart Armstrong]], who had tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54453593|title=Scotland trio out after positive test|website=BBC Sport |date=7 October 2020}}</ref> A month later, Christie returned to the team and scored Scotland's only goal in the Euro 2020 play-off final against [[Serbia national football team|Serbia]]; they won the tie on a penalty shootout after a 1–1 draw, qualifying for a major tournament for the first time in 22 years.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Scots win for whole nation – Christie|work=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/54926809|date=12 November 2020|access-date=13 November 2020}}</ref>

Christie was a member of Scotland's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2020]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4210994/2021/06/01/scotlands-full-26-man-euro-2020-squad/|title=Scotland's full 26-man Euro 2020 squad|date=1 June 2021|access-date=15 June 2024|website=The Athletic}}</ref> making one appearance at the tournament in the team's opening 2–0 defeat to the Czech Republic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51197776 |title=Euro 2020: Scotland 0–2 Czech Republic – Patrik Schick double downs Steve Clarke's side |date=13 June 2021 |access-date=15 June 2024 |website=BBC Sport}}</ref>

On 7 June 2024, Christie was named in Scotland's squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/record-breaking-goalkeeper-gordon-out-scotland-euro-2024-squad-2024-06-07/|title=Record-breaking goalkeeper Gordon out of Scotland's Euro 2024 squad|date=7 June 2024|access-date=15 June 2024|website=Reuters}}</ref> A week later, he started the opening match of the tournament against [[Germany national football team|Germany]],<ref>{{Cite web
|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c844x4y3ee3t|title=Ruthless Germany humble 10-man Scotland in Euro 2024 opener|website=BBC Sport|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref> winning his [[Scottish FA International Roll of Honour|50th cap for Scotland]] (as did teammate [[Scott McTominay]]) in the 5–1 loss.<ref>{{Cite web
|url= https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/germany-scotland-live-updates-euro-2024-score-result/zQ8kQPr4CV1U/YgK5BMDMAq0d/
|title= Ryan Christie: Germany were 'pretty impressive'
|website=New York Times
|date=14 June 2024
|access-date=15 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2203012638-25d41b72cf92-1000--germany-5-1-scotland-hosts-hit-ground-running-in-munich/|title=Germany 5–1 Scotland: Hosts hit ground running in Munich|website=[[UEFA]]|date=14 June 2024|access-date=6 September 2024}}</ref> He went on to appear as a substitute against both [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] as Scotland finished bottom of [[UEFA Euro 2024 Group A|Group A]] with one point from three matches.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/news/028e-1b2c127c5b92-e020507872a2-1000--scotland-1-1-switzerland-clarke-s-men-keep-group-a-hopes-/|title=Scotland 1–1 Switzerland: Clarke's men keep Group A hopes alive|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA|date=19 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uefa.com/euro2024/match/2036186--scotland-vs-hungary/lineups/|title=Scotland vs Hungary: Line-ups|access-date=24 June 2024|website=UEFA|date=23 June 2024}}</ref>

